Great Leader's Revival
Two hundred years have now passed since the Battle of Waterloo in London, Napoleon's disastrous defeat in that battle severely damaged France's pride, to the extent that General De Gaulle did not even mention it in writing the history of the French army.
Even so, if you recognize "great" as some kind of personal quality, then both Napoleon and De Gaulle could be considered the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is no such thing as a "Great Leader".
In Marx's view, France's class struggle created an environment where an "extraordinary mediocrity" like Napoleon could become a hero.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon did not stand out as an especially outstanding general, his victories should be attributed to the courage and selfless spirit of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.
Regardless of whether Napoleon is great, we need to determine whether greatness can be used to describe any leader.
If the answer is affirmative, then who could be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believes that a Great Leader must meet two particularly important standards.
First, can this leader discern historical trends?
Otto von Bismarck did, so did his German compatriot Konrad Adenauer; borrowing Bismarck's unforgettable phrase, both heard the rustling of the Almighty's cloak.
Second, has this leader made significant decisions?
If a leader is forced to make decisions, neither can he be blamed for them nor can he take credit for them.
Therefore, the key issue is whether the leader has the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons and make the right decision on behalf of the nation.
General De Gaulle therefore deserves a place on any list of Great Leaders.
He virtually single-handedly led France out of the post-war period of decline.
After Napoleon's defeat at the Battle of Waterloo two hundred years ago, which damaged France's pride, some consider him and General De Gaulle as the greatest leaders in history due to their personal qualities.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, General De Gaulle imparted a new worldview to the French, thereby establishing their position in the post-war global order.
In fact, both De Gaulle and Churchill's ultimate impact on shaping their own country's worldview is somewhat overstated.
Their successors would years later view the world in a way of checking rational inquiry and distorting decision-making — as well as their own nation's role.
As a result, their successors were unable to achieve achievements comparable to those of the two Great Leaders.
But there is another British Prime Minister who can be compared to them: Margaret Thatcher, a highly controversial figure, equally admired and detested by people.
Even her resignation 25 years ago was a result of the internal resistance from her own cabinet and party.
But a great leader does not necessarily need the approval of everyone.
In fact, even her critics cannot deny her impact.
Besides being the first female Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, she was almost the first female Prime Minister of other countries around the world, Thatcher helped turn around Britain's economic downturn.
In addition, her attack on overly powerful unions enhanced the country's manageability at a time when it seemed to be sliding into turmoil and chaos.
In light of this, she undoubtedly has the right to be considered a "Great Leader".
Similarly, despite being far from flawless, Deng Xiaoping also has the right to be considered a Great Leader.
Aside from assisting Mao Zedong in his nefarious endeavors, Deng played a decisive role in ordering the Tiananmen Square Massacre in 1989.
But Deng simultaneously revitalized the market, putting China on the unprecedented path of development and prosperity that would ultimately allow billions of Chinese people to escape poverty.
Many people consider Lee Kuan Yew, the founding father and long-time Prime Minister of Singapore, to be a truly great leader, even though he may have aspired to make a greater impact on a larger stage.
In fact, a country's size seems to make little difference in determining whether someone can be a Great Leader.
When I said that small countries like Luxembourg are unlikely to produce Great Leaders, I certainly did not mean to be derogatory, especially given the country's relatively low-key political climate.
The United States' vast territory provides ample scope for the emergence of a Great Leader.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a great deal.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — although hardly towering intellectual giants — demonstrated outstanding judgment in establishing the post-war international order that has underpinned world peace for several decades.
Other people, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possess exceptional gifts - the ability to inspire and the art of persuasion.
John F. Kennedy was a man of many talents.
He completed a great task: resolving the Cuban Missile Crisis.
He possesses an unmatched gift for inspiring others; in fact, his assassination after his death only solidified his legacy.
In South Africa, no one has yet been considered a great figure since the death of President Mandela, who embodied courage, authority, and the graciousness of a magnanimous leader.
In fact, he was the most charismatic leader I have ever seen; the other two, former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former US Secretary of State Colin Powell, are either Africans or African Americans.
So then?
The only one who can claim greatness is the de facto leader of the EU, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at the outset but made few mistakes when it came to making important decisions.
Helmut Kohl formulated generous terms for German unification; Merkel opposed Putin during his invasion of Ukraine and took a tolerant stance on the migrant crisis.
I disagree with Marx and Tolstoy.
Political leaders – the exercisers of political power – can alter the course of events, for better or for worse.
Merkel is the most obvious example today, showing the way forward for Europe as it confronts a high-stakes survival crisis.
